we might want to repeat sorting for each N several times and choose the average runtime due to the following reasons:

  1. Because we are working with random numbers so we need to get the repeat the process more than once to make sure that the result that we are getting will apply to all the cases not just the one we are using.
  2. By choosing the average we avoided incorrect statistical sampling because when we took the average we took a value that resembles all the sample. we didn't take the min, max or an outlier.

The reason why I think insertion sort is a good algorithm and used it is because it's very popular algorithm, i wanted to experience with an alogrithm that was mentioned in the book and i really enjoy implementing inseration sort. It has a lot of space to enhace its performance easily.

Also an important thing that I need to mention is that I have used two types of N in this part of the example because i wasn't sure what N is required. It makes sense to use a subset from the original N to be able to see the chaneg between the runtime differnece of the two implementation. But again we can also experience with a new N and i wasn't sure of what's required to be honst and i loved to experience a bit.

Regarding the number of times I have repeated this experiment is 200 times for each N and 50 times for the subset of N. I felt that it's important to repeat it because with repeating the experiment more than once we get more accurate results.

We have actually have figured out some amazing results from this experiment After plotting the O(N) , O(N^2) , O(N log N) we actually see that

  1. The runtime of (n log n) is always the smallest.
  2. The runtime of (n) follows the runtime of (n log n).
  3. The runtime of (n^2) is actually the largest.

HW2¶

In this exercise, I would like to choose the sort sorting algorithm. Initially it uses the Timsort Algorithm which has the best case of O(N), average case of O(N log N), worst case of O(N log N). Timsort is a hybrid stable sorting algorithm, derived from merge sort and insertion sort, designed to perform well on many kinds of real-world data. It was implemented by Tim Peters in 2002 for use in the Python programming language. The algorithm finds subsequences of the data that are already ordered (runs) and uses them to sort the remainder more efficiently.

In this exercise we will measure the runtime of the sort algorithm. by repeating the process of storing the beginning and ending times in lists then calculate the differece so we can get the average of the difference and measure the runtime with it.

In order to prove the theta notation we need to prove the big O notation and the big omega notation. so in code we need to prove that: c1(n^3+n^2) <= 3n^3+n <= c2(n^3+n^2)
